{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628020"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:54:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:54:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17178"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17178"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9868"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75555"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9868"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61070"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"212"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5858"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23133"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75555"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35 year old woman presents complaining of headache.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most characteristic feature of tension-type headaches?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bilateral location","Associated nausea and vomiting","Pulsating quality","Worsening with physical activity","Unilateral location"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral location\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic feature of tension-type headaches, often described as \u0027band-like\u0027 pressure or tightness around the head. The bilateral nature helps distinguish it from other primary headache disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAssociated nausea and vomiting\u003C/strong\u003E are not typical features of tension-type headaches. These symptoms are more commonly associated with migraine headaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epulsating quality\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of migraine headaches. Tension-type headaches are typically described as pressing or tightening in quality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWorsening with physical activity\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic feature of migraines, not tension-type headaches. Tension-type headaches typically remain stable with activity, an important distinguishing feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eunilateral location\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with migraine or cluster headaches. While tension-type headaches can occasionally be unilateral, they are much more commonly bilateral.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important features of tension-type headaches include mild to moderate intensity, no significant interference with daily activities, and frequent association with stress or muscle tension. Treatment typically involves simple analgesics and lifestyle modifications including stress management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tension-type headaches are typically bilateral, pressing or tightening in quality, and mild to moderate in intensity.","Tension-type headaches are not usually associated with nausea, vomiting, or photophobia.","Physical activity does not usually worsen tension-type headaches."],"references":["Ashina S, Mitsikostas DD, Lee MJ, Yamani N, Wang SJ, Messina R, Ashina H, Buse DC, Pozo-Rosich P, Jensen RH, Diener HC, Lipton RB. Tension-type headache. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2021 Mar 25;7(1):24. doi: 10.1038/s41572-021-00257-2. PMID: 33767185.","Chowdhury D. Tension type headache. Ann Indian Acad Neurol. 2012 Aug;15(Suppl 1):S83-8. doi: 10.4103/0972-2327.100023. PMID: 23024570; PMCID: PMC3444224.","Loder E, Rizzoli P. Tension-type headache. BMJ. 2008 Jan 12;336(7635):88-92. doi: 10.1136/bmj.39412.705868.AD. PMID: 18187725; PMCID: PMC2190284."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61070"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17178"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61070"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T10:10:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T10:10:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9868"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75555"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":